Pleistocene climate oscillations and habitat connectivity contributed to avian beta-diversity in the megadiverse Colombian Paramo ecosystems

Edna V. Calpa-Anaguano,
Catherine H. Graham,
Fernando R. da Silva,
First published: 26 October 2021
https://doi.org/10.1111/jbi.14251

Handling Editor: : Walter Jetz

Sections
PDF
Tools
Share

Abstract

Aim

The role of evolutionary history in shaping the patterns of species distributions is generally explored at coarse spatial extents. However, at small spatial extents, the combined effects of history and ecological processes on local diversity has received less attention. We test the relative importance of historical and ecological factors on the spatial distribution of bird taxonomic (TβD) and phylogenetic (PβD) β-diversity on Paramo ecosystems.

Location

South-western Colombia.

Taxon

Andean bird species.

Methods

Using point occurrence data for 175 bird species recorded in 11 Paramos, we calculated TβD and PβD. We used a lineage through time plot to evaluate the association between bird species richness and the time of Andean uplift and Quaternary climatic oscillations. To capture range dynamics associated with past climate oscillations, we delimited paramos using connectivity matrices based on four distance criteria (i.e. paramos connected at 20, 25, 35 and 55 km apart) to compute Moran's eigenvectors maps. Then, we evaluated the relative importance of altitude, past climatic oscillations, current climate and connectivity on the spatial distribution of avian TβD and PβD.

Results

Two-thirds of the bird species in the paramos are recent and emerged after the late Miocene/early Pliocene. The average TβD was four times higher than the average PβD indicating that paramo assemblages harbour distinct, but closely related, species. We found that distribution of β-diversity had a spatial structure resulting in two groups of paramos – one in the north of our study area containing four paramos and other in the south with seven paramos. This spatial structure together with past climate conditions explained the variation of both TβD and PβD.

Main conclusions

Our results are consistent with the hypothesis that patterns of β-diversity reflect the complex history of Andean region including mountain uplift and climatic oscillations in the Pleistocene. We demonstrated that the integration of different facets of β-diversity into a community ecology framework provides new insights about the historical and ecological factors responsible for generating the patterns of species distribution.

1 INTRODUCTION

A key challenge in ecological research is determining the relative importance of historical and contemporary processes in shaping geographical variation in biodiversity (HilleRisLambers et al., 2012; Ricklefs, 1987; Wiens & Donoghue, 2004). On the one hand, historical factors, such as uplift of mountain ranges and Quaternary climatic oscillations, impacted the rates of speciation, extinction and dispersal, affecting species richness and composition (Benício et al., 2021; Graham et al., 2006; Hoorn et al., 2010; Rangel et al., 2018; Ricklefs, 1987). On the other hand, contemporary factors, such as species–environment associations and species interactions, determine which species can coexist in a given assemblage (HilleRisLambers et al., 2012; Weiher & Keddy, 1995). Evaluating multiple dimensions (e.g. taxonomic and phylogenetic) of β-diversity (i.e. variation in species composition between two communities) is a promising approach to tease apart the importance of historical and contemporary processes that generate and maintain patterns of species distributions (Benício et al., 2021; da Silva et al., 2014; Graham & Fine, 2008; Penone et al., 2016; Qian et al., 2013; Swenson et al., 2012; Weinstein et al., 2014). For example, Weinstein et al. (2014) found that high β-diversity in all dimensions resulted from hummingbird adaptation to different environments in isolated assemblages in the northern Andes. Da Silva et al. (2014), in an evaluation of taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity, found that speciation, environmental filtering and dispersal limitation were complementary drivers of amphibian assemblages in the Brazilian Atlantic Forest. These examples withstanding, multiple dimensions of β-diversity have been poorly explored in mountain regions that are considered cradles (i.e. areas of especially rapid species origination), museums (i.e. areas of especially long-term persistence of species) and graves (i.e. areas with especially high rates of extinction) of biodiversity (Fjeldså et al., 2012; Rahbek, Borregaard, Antonelli, et al., 2019; Rahbek, Borregaard, Colwell, et al., 2019; Rangel et al., 2018).

The paramo ecosystem in the tropical Andes of South America is an excellent study system for evaluating the importance of historical and contemporary processes shaping current patterns of species distributions. The paramo ecosystem hosts many threatened bird species (Fundación ProAves, 2014), and thus, greater knowledge about the origin and maintenance of its diversity is critical for conservation. This ecosystem, dominated by grasslands above the forest tree-line on isolated mountain-tops above 2800–4700 m from Costa Rica to Peru, has been divided into 11 biogeographic districts (Hazzi et al., 2018; Madriñán et al., 2013). The timing of mountain building in the northern Andes (from ~23 to 6 Ma, Gregory-Wodzicki, 2000; Hoorn et al., 2010), in conjunction with Pleistocene climatic oscillations, had a strong effect on the diversification of Andean biota (Fjeldså et al., 2012; Hazzi et al., 2018; Madriñán et al., 2013; Van der Hammen, 1974). In particular, the final phase of the Andean uplift during the late Miocene/early Pliocene (Gregory-Wodzicki, 2000) created isolated ‘sky islands’ surrounded by drier valleys, which act as dispersal barriers (Hazzi et al., 2018). Quaternary climate change caused repeated range expansion and contraction, allowing down-slope migration through the drier valleys (Hazzi et al., 2018; Hooghiemstra et al., 2006; Van der Hammen, 1974). Under this scenario, speciation rates were not constant over time but were related to historical events (Weir, 2006). Information contained in time-calibrated phylogenies, allows us to explore if increases in speciation are associated with the Andean uplift and historical connectivity of paramos (Paradis, 1997; Rabosky, 2006).

Most studies exploring the influence of historical events on the origin and maintenance of paramo biodiversity have considered the entire paramo region, making it difficult to evaluate small-scale ecological processes. Evaluating smaller spatial extents provides the opportunity to integrate biogeographical and ecological approaches to infer the role of different processes generating bird diversity (e.g. Benício et al., 2021; Ricklefs & Jenkins, 2011; Warren et al., 2014; Weeks et al., 2016). The spatial distribution of β-diversity provides insight into the relative importance of historical mechanism, such as speciation, and contemporary ones, notably dispersal, on spatial variation among paramo assemblages. Speciation and dispersal can generate four scenarios related to spatial distribution of taxonomic (TβD) and phylogenetic (PβD) beta diversities (Figure S1): (i) high TβD and low PβD – paramo assemblages may have different species compositions but harbour closely related species due to recent allopatric speciation in historical connected among assemblages; (ii) high TβD and PβD – paramo assemblages may harbour completely different lineages (taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity; Graham & Fine, 2008) due to in situ radiation and long-term geographic barriers limiting recent historical connectivity; (iii) low TβD and high PβD – paramo assemblages may harbour phylogenetically distinct species with small geographic ranges which are dispersal limited by geographic barriers (e.g. relic population that persisted in only a few places) and (iv) low TβD and PβD – paramo assemblages may have similar species composition (i.e. biotic homogenization) due to no dispersal limitation.

Here, we test the relative importance of these historical and ecological factors on the spatial distribution of bird taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity based on 11 paramo ecosystems of south-western Colombia. Colombia contains the most extensive area of paramos in the Neotropics including seven of the eleven biogeographic districts delimited based on the distributional data of 4644 vertebrate and angiosperm species (Jiménez-Rivillas et al., 2018). The study region encompasses the Colombian massif and ‘Nudo de los Pastos’ which meet at the intersection of distinct cordilleras. Given their unique geographic position, they have been recognized as a hotspot of diversification and endemism (Delgado et al., 2008; González-Orozco, 2021; Hazzi et al., 2018; Jiménez-Rivillas et al., 2018; Morales et al., 2007). We hypothesize that the geographic position at the intersection of cordilleras and Pleistocene climatic oscillation are important factors associated with the current patterns of species distributions (Fjeldså et al., 2012; Hazzi et al., 2018; Kattan et al., 2004; Van der Hammen, 1974). Specifically, we predict that taxonomic β-diversity will be high between assemblages due to dry valleys constraining dispersal across paramos ecosystems. This is expected because mountains surrounded by dry valleys have increased speciation rates and endemism compared with those surrounded by mesic habitats (e.g. Fjeldså et al., 2012; Hoorn et al., 2010; Jetz et al., 2012; Quintero & Jetz, 2018; Figure 1). Conversely, we predict that low phylogenetic β-diversity between assemblages is due to the down-slope dispersal of bird lineages through the drier valleys during climatic oscillations that facilitated past connection between neighbouring paramos (Hazzi et al., 2018; Van der Hammen, 1974; Figure 1). Based on this scenario, we expect a positive association between phylogenetic β-diversity and geographical distance (e.g. distance decay of similarity; Nekola & White, 1999). Furthermore, we predict that current climatic variation will be associated with spatial distribution of taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity if there are no barriers constraining species dispersal among paramos. In this case, species composition will vary in relation to differences among local conditions of paramos and the successful establishment of any species will depend on its physiological tolerance to climatic conditions or other mechanisms such as biotic interactions (e.g. Keddy, 1992).

2 MATERIALS AND METHODS

2.1 Study area

Paramo ecosystems in the region range in temperature between 0 and 12°C and annual total precipitation between 1000 and 2000 mm. Paramos are subdivided based on climatic variables and elevation into three zones (Delgado et al., 2008; Morales et al., 2007): (i) subparamo – formed by shrubs and small trees scattered; (ii) paramo – characterized by the presence of acaulescent rosette plant types and tussock grasses; and (iii) super-paramo – located below the snowline – characterized by the sparse vegetation, stony soil and presence of cushion plants.

Bird occurrences were recorded in 11 paramos in the Andes mountain range over the Colombian massif and ‘Nudo de los Pastos’ in Nariño and Cauca departments (see Figure 1; Table 1; Table S1). Colombian massif and ‘Nudo de los Pastos’ have a tectonic origin with volcanic geomorphological formations located within the Paramo biogeographic province (González-Orozco, 2021; IGAC, 1997; Morrone, 2014) and Narinõ – Putumayo district (sensu Morales et al., 2007). The Colombian massif and ‘Nudo de los Pastos’ have a key role in Colombia biogeography because they are at the intersection of mountain cordilleras. The Colombian massif contains the intersection between the Central and Eastern Cordilleras while the ‘Nudo de los Pastos’ contains the intersection between the Central and Western Cordillera (Delgado et al., 2008; Morales et al., 2007). There is mounting evidence that the intersections of cordilleras, together with alterations in the vegetation during glacial periods and active volcanic activities, have resulted in isolation of biotas contributing to high rates of diversification and endemism in this region (Delgado et al., 2008; Hazzi et al., 2018; Morales et al., 2007; Stattersfield et al., 1998).

The average linear geographic distance between the 11 paramos we evaluated is 53.5 ± 30.5 km. In each paramo, four sampling stations were delimited along an altitudinal transect encompassing zones and ecotones of Andean high forest, shrubland, and grassland (Figure 1). We used GPS elevation data of the first and fourth sampling stations along the altitudinal transect in each paramo (Figure 1; Table 1) to determine maximum altitude (MAAL-station 1), minimum altitude (MIAL-station 4) and altitudinal range (difference between MAAL and MIAL: RAAL).

2.2 Bird distribution data

Bird sampling was carried out within each of the 11 paramos for 7 to 9 days from January to July 2015 using visual and auditory surveys, and mist nets. Surveys were done during peak bird activity from 5:30 to 9:30 h and from 15:30 to 18:30 h, using 6 count points of 25 m radius in each sampling station of dense habitats (high Andean forest and dense shrubs stations) and 50 m of radius in each station of low shrubs and grasslands. Count points were separated by 150 m. Mist nets (12 m × 2.5 m and 32 mm mesh eye) were placed between the counting points. Nets were opened for 6–18 h over 9 days. All sampling was done on days without extensive rain or wind following standard avian sampling protocols. These data form part of a large project of the Universidad de Nariño, Instituto de Investigación de Recursos Biológicos Alexander von Humboldt, 2016 where they are curated and made publicly available (2016, http://doi.org/10.15472/zmnvox).

In total, 175 bird species were recorded in 11 paramos (Table S2). Given that our study area was relatively small most species have geographical distributions that extend beyond the study area (Calderón-Leytón et al., 2011). However, considering that we are interested in how historical and ecological processes have shaped the current spatial distribution of taxonomic and phylogenetic assemblages at small spatial extent, evaluating only part of species geographical distribution does not affect our findings.

2.2.1 Current climate conditions

We obtained current climate variables from WorldClim 2 (Fick & Hijmans; https://www.worldclim.org/) at 1 km spatial resolution (Table S2). We selected eight climatic variables based on previous studies that evaluated Andean bird distributions (e.g. Graham et al., 2009, 2010; Leprieur et al., 2012; Table S2): annual mean temperature (AMT), mean diurnal range (MDR), temperature seasonality (TS), temperature annual range (TAR), annual precipitation (AP), precipitation seasonality (PS), precipitation of warmest quarter (PWQ), precipitation of coldest quarter (PCQ). We calculated difference between Pleistocene and current climate variables to determine the climatic oscillation over time.

2.2.2 Past climate conditions

We obtained climatic variables of the last glacial maximum (LGM) 22,000 years ago (Community Climate System Model – CCSM4) from WorldClim 2 (Fick & Hijmans, 2017) at 1 km spatial resolution (Table S2). We selected the same eight climatic variables extracted for current climatic conditions. Following Godinho and da Silva (2018), we subtracted LGM from current climate variables to determine the climatic oscillation over this period. Negative values indicate that climate variables are higher currently than in the past, whereas positive values indicate that climate variables were higher in the past than currently.

2.2.3 Connectivity

The paramos of Colombia, currently only 5% of their former area, were connected during the LGM when cool forest conditions existed at much lower altitudes than at present and paramos had a broader distribution (Flantua et al., 2015; Hazzi et al., 2018; Hooghiemstra et al., 2006; Van der Hammen, 1974). Therefore, connectivity among paramos was dynamic, resulting from paramo expansion and contraction over time. To capture this dynamism, we delimited four spatial structures ranging from low to high connectivity among paramos based on four distance criteria (i.e. sites connected at 20, 35, 50 and 65 km apart; Figure 2). These distance criteria represent a gradient of connectivity among paramos with 20 km representing the lower connectivity, whereas 65 km represent the higher connectivity (Figure 2). We weighted the spatial relationships among sampling locations by geographic distance using spatial weighting matrix (SWM) in ‘spdep’ R package (Bivand & Wong, 2018). These SWM matrices were used to generate Moran's eigenvector maps (MEMs) using ‘adespatial’ R package (Dray et al., 2020). MEMs can be used as predictor variables to study spatial patterns of the response variable (Dray et al., 2006, 2012). To avoid model overfitting, we performed a forward selection with double stopping criterion to only select MEMs that significantly explained the variation in taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity (Bauman et al., 2018; Blanchet et al., 2008). The selected MEMs were used, separately for each class of spatial structure, as a surrogate of connectivity in the subsequent analysis (Figure 2).

2.2.4 Reducing dimensionality

We performed three separate principal component analyses to reduce data dimensionality of current climate (AMT, MDR, TS, TAR, AP, PS, PWQ and PCQ), past climate oscillation (AMT, MDR, TS, TAR, AP, PS, PWQ and PCQ) and altitude (MAAL, MIAL and RAAL) variables. We found that the first principal components explained 53%, 48% and 51% of the variation in current climate, past climate oscillation and altitude, respectively (Table S2). The PCs of current climate variables represented an axis of environmental harshness with negative values indicating high TAR, whereas positive values indicated high AP and high precipitation in the warmest quarter. The PCs of past climate oscillation also represented an axis of environmental harshness, negative values indicating higher TAR in the past than currently, whereas positive values indicated lower AP and PWQ during the Pleistocene than present day. The PCs of altitude represented an axis with negative values, indicating low maximum elevation, whereas positive values indicated high maximum elevation and altitudinal ranges. For subsequent analysis, we used the first PCs of each ordination as surrogates for current climate, past climate oscillation and altitudinal gradients (Figure 2).

2.2.5 Taxonomic beta diversity (TβD)

We calculated TβD between bird communities using the Simpson dissimilarity index (Lennon et al., 2001), which measures the diversity generated by species replacement between communities. βsim is one of the most used measures to describe spatial turnover because it is not sensitive to differences in species richness between localities (Lennon et al., 2001). When all species are shared βsim = 1, and when no species is shared βsim = 0.

2.2.6 Phylogenetic beta diversity (PβD)

We pruned the time-calibrated tree proposed by Jetz et al. (2012, https://birdtree.org/) to include the 175 bird species recorded in the 11 paramos. Only three (Arremon assimilis, Arremon atricapillus and Scytalopus opacus) of the 175 species were not present in this tree so we inserted these species as polytomies at the genus level (Figure 2). We calculated phylogenetic turnover using PhyloSorTurn, which measures the diversity generated by the replacement of lineages between communities (Leprieur et al., 2012). PhyloSorTurn = 1 indicates that two communities do not share any branch in the phylogenetic tree, and PhyloSorTurn = 0 indicates that two communities share all branches of the phylogenetic tree.

2.2.7 Standardized effect size (SES)

We calculated SES for TβD and PβD by randomizing species co-occurrences 999 times while maintaining both sample richness and occurrence frequency using the independent swap algorithm (Kembel, 2009) in ‘picante’ R package (Kembel et al., 2010). SES values greater than 1.96 indicate a higher β-diversity than expected by chance, whereas SES values below −1.96 indicate a lower β-diversity than expected by chance.

2.2.8 Lineage through time (LTT)

We computed a LTT plot using the function mltt.plot in the ‘ape’ R package (Paradis & Schliep, 2018) to visualize patterns of lineage diversification through time. Our goal was to explore whether signals of temporal increase in the number of species (e.g. change in the slope of the line) corresponded to estimated periods of Andean uplift and/or climatic oscillations in the Pleistocene. We are aware that including only lineages from sampled paramos (i.e. incomplete taxon sampling) might bias the estimation of lineage accumulation. However, we emphasize that are not trying to provide a complete understating of bird diversification in the Andes but trying to associate the pattern of lineage accumulation over time with estimated periods of historic events. Thus, LTT remains a good approach for inferring the relationship between periods of increased species diversification and geologic events hypothesized to influence speciation in the Andean region (e.g. Benício et al., 2021; Skeels & Cardillo, 2019).

2.3 Relative importance of current climate, past climate oscillations, altitude and geographic distance to taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity

We used a distance-based partial redundancy analysis (db-pRDA) with variance partitioning to estimate the relative importance of connectivity, current climate, past climatic oscillations and altitude in explaining variation in TβD and PβD. Distance-based partial redundancy analysis is considered a direct extension of multiple regression analysis to model multivariate response data (i.e. non-Euclidean dissimilarity indices) that controls for the effect of one predictor while analysing the effect of other on species composition variation (Legendre & Anderson, 1999). Variance partitioning estimates the relative importance of unique and common contributions of the sets of predictors in explaining variation in TβD and PβD (Borcard et al., 1992). We performed db-pRDA and variation partitioning separately for each class of spatial structure (Figure 2). All analyses were performed using the ‘vegan’ R package (Oksanen et al., 2019) in R v. 4.0 (R Core Team, 2020).

3 RESULTS

Species richness in paramos ranged from 40 to 87 (52.1 ± 13.2 SD; Figure 2). The LTT plot indicates that two-thirds of the 175 bird species found in paramos originated after the late Miocene/early Pliocene (Figure 2). The average TβD (Mean = 0.44, SD = 0.07, Min = 0.29, Max = 0.60) was four times higher than the average PβD (Mean = 0.11, SD = 0.04, Min = 0.02, Max = 0.22; Figure 2). These results indicate that paramo assemblages harbour different, but closely related species. In general, the observed values of the TβD and PβD were similar to those expected by chance (Figure S2). MEMs indicate that distribution of β-diversity in our study region has a spatial structure. We identified groups of paramos – one in the north containing four paramos and other in the south containing seven paramos (Figure 3). MEMs were associated with past climate conditions indicating that paramos located in the north had a greater temperature range and lower AP in the past than those located in the south (Tables S2 and S3). Variation partitioning showed that MEMs and past climate conditions explained on average 7.5 ± 0.57% and 8.75 ± 2.21% of the spatial distribution of TβD and 12 ± 5.29% and 9.5 ± 1.29% of the spatial distribution of PβD, respectively (Figure 4).

4 DISCUSSION

High taxonomic β-diversity, in conjunction with relatively low phylogenetic β-diversity, across bird assemblages indicates that both speciation and dispersal influence diversity patterns in paramo ecosystems. The LTT indicates that the splitting age of two-thirds of the bird species overlap the late Miocene/early Pliocene, suggesting that the final phase of the Andean uplift had an important role in bird diversification in this ecosystem (Fjeldså, 1994; Fjeldså et al., 2012; Fjeldså & Rahbek, 1997; Hazzi et al., 2018; Ribas et al., 2007). Several studies have shown that young bird radiations are common in mountainous regions, which are centres of endemism and speciation resulting from geological and orogenetic dynamics that created dispersal barriers and opportunities for reduced gene flow (Antonelli et al., 2018; Fjeldså et al., 2012; Graham et al., 2014; Hoorn et al., 2010; Ricklefs, 2003; Weir, 2006). In terms of dispersal, the spatial structure of paramos, with a northern and southern group, indicates that dispersal limitation likely explains patterns of β-diversity. β-diversity seems to be associated with range expansion and contraction of paramos during cyclic climatic changes, such that taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity are more distinct as distance between paramos increases from a north-south direction. Taken together, our results reinforce the idea that integrating historical signals into community ecology can provide insight into the relative importance of evolutionary and ecological factors associated with patterns of present-day species distribution (da Silva et al., 2014; Graham & Fine, 2008; Penone et al., 2016; Weinstein et al., 2014).

Lower phylogenetic β-diversity relative to taxonomic β-diversity is consistent with species being replaced (turnover) by closely related ones. Graham et al. (2009), evaluating hummingbird communities in the Andes, and Qian et al. (2013), evaluating regional floras in North America, also found that despite the large differences in species composition, isolated assemblages are largely composed of the same phylogenetic components (i.e. the same genera and families). This pattern is similar for paramo flora of recent origin, from 3 to 5 Ma, where isolation has been suggested as a main factor explaining the low number of endemic genera, but high species turnover and endemism (Londoño et al., 2014; Morales et al., 2007; Van der Hammen, 1997). This scenario is often explained by vicariance events resulting in isolation between mountains or on opposite sides of the same mountain (i.e. allopatric speciation) and divergence from differential selection along elevational gradient within the same mountain (i.e. parapatric speciation; Fjeldså & Rahbek, 2006; Garciá-Moreno & Fjeldså, 2000; Hazzi et al., 2018; Kattan & Franco, 2004; Moritz et al., 2000; Rahbek, 1995; Terborgh, 1977). Although the LTT indicates that the uplift history of the Andes had an important role in speciation burst since Miocene, our data do not allow us to differentiate between allopatric and parapatric speciation. However, both models of speciation are considered plausible in the diversification of the Andean avifauna (Dehling et al., 2014; Fjeldså et al., 2012; Garciá-Moreno & Fjeldså, 2000; Hazzi et al., 2018; Ribas et al., 2007). In allopatric speciation, considered the dominant mode of speciation in birds, the range of a widespread ancestor is fragmented as result of mountain uplift resulting in the origination of new species (see García-Moreno & Fjeldså, 2000; Hazzi et al., 2018; Ribas et al., 2007; Winger et al., 2015). In this scenario, speciation would increase the taxonomic β-diversity, but not the phylogenetic β-diversity between paramos. For parapatric speciation, elevational gradients promote a diversity of ecosystems and each ecosystem has its unique specialized bird composition (Dehling et al., 2014; Fjeldså et al., 2012; Herzog et al., 2005; McCain, 2009; Terborgh, 1977). In this scenario, if speciation occurs along elevational bands within the same mountain, then it would increase the taxonomic β-diversity between isolated paramos. The origin of a new species would not affect phylogenetic β-diversity because the new species would belong to the same genus already present in other paramos. Thus, current patterns of β-diversity cannot be understood based only on a particular event or mechanism. In fact, several studies emphasized that Andean avifauna has been shaped by complex orographic and climate dynamics (Antonelli et al., 2009; Chesser, 2000; Hazzi et al., 2018; Hoorn et al., 2010; Ribas et al., 2007).

Recent studies have suggested that dispersal limitation in the Andes, occurring after major uplift episodes, is an important driver of Neotropical bird distribution (Cadena et al., 2016; Oswald et al., 2017; Smith et al., 2014). Bird taxonomic and phylogenetic β-diversity was more similar within the northern and southern group of paramos identified in our spatial analyses then between these distinct groups. According to Soininen et al. (2007), decay of community similarity with geographical distance can be the result of three mechanisms: (i) decreasing similarity in environmental conditions (e.g. species sorting); (ii) increasing number of dispersal barriers and (iii) random dispersal (e.g. neutral theory, Hubbell, 2001). Among the three, we infer that species sorting has the smallest contribution because of the lack of an association between current climatic conditions and patterns of β-diversity. In contrast, the geological and climatalogical history of Colombia massif and Nudo de los Pastos – intersection of cordilleras, river canyons, and past climatic oscillations – indicate that dispersal barriers might have an important role in the decay of community similarity with geographical distance. For example, the first axis of db-pRDA indicates that the paramos P10 and P11 have high community dissimilarity in relation to other paramos. One possibility is that Guaira River, that geographically isolates these paramos from the others, might limit the dispersion of some species. The existence of areas of endemism and their hierarchical organization (i.e. Colombian massif and the south of Central Cordillera) also represents strong evidence that biotas are organized in response to past or current physical and biological forces (Jiménez-Rivillas et al., 2018; Kreft & Jetz, 2010; Van der Hammen, 1997). For example, the northern and southern group of paramos identified in our spatial analyses are congruent with the Northern Ecuadorian Paramo and Main Central Cordillera biogeographical districts (Jiménez-Rivillas et al., 2018; Morrone, 2021), and the existence of a transition zone between the Ecuadorian and Colombian Andes (Morales et al., 2007; Van der Hammen, 1997). Furthermore, several studies have described that between 21,000 and 14,000 yr BP, there was a very cold but dry period during which the Paramo ecosystems covered a much greater area than it does today, and that many of the currently isolated paramos were united permitting dispersal among them (Hazzi et al., 2018; Hooghiemstra et al., 2006; Van der Hammen, 1974). This scenario is supported by molecular studies of widespread Andean bird species that have neighbouring populations in close geographic proximity (Pérez-Emán, 2005; Ribas et al., 2007; Winger et al., 2015). Thus, it is possible that some areas may be presently unsuitable for the dispersal of birds across the paramos, but under past climatic conditions, they were substantially more likely to allow for ecological connectivity of populations between close assemblages (e.g. Hazzi et al., 2018; Hooghiemstra et al., 2006; Van der Hammen, 1974) than distant ones. This mechanism has also been suggested to have promoted diversification in Andean birds generally (Chesser, 2000; Garcia-Moreno & Fjeldså, 2000; Ribas et al., 2007). For the last possibility, random dispersal proposed by neutral theory (Hubbell, 2001) requires knowledge about bird abundance that is not available for our data set. Therefore, we do not discard random dispersal as a factor affecting the distance decay relationship jointly with barriers limiting dispersal since they are not mutually exclusive mechanisms (Soininen et al., 2007).

5 CONCLUSION

Overall, patterns of β-diversity distribution reflect the complex history of Andean region including mountain uplift and climatic oscillations in the Pleistocene that have influenced diversification rates and dispersal among paramos (Antonelli et al., 2009; Hazzi et al., 2018; Hoorn et al., 2010; Ribas et al., 2007). Over the past decades, the development and advances of molecular methods and tools delimiting phylogenetic relationships has provided new insights on the origins and geographic history of bird speciation and dispersal in the Andes (Garcıá-Moreno & Fjeldså, 2000; Pérez-Emán, 2005; Ribas et al., 2007; Winger et al., 2015). However, there are still few studies evaluating how these historical processes have influenced the current spatial distribution of taxonomic and phylogenetic assemblages in this region (e.g. Kattan et al., 2004 at broad spatial extent). Here, we show that integrating historical and ecological biogeography with different facets of β-diversity can provide some insight into the importance of evolutionary and contemporary factors shaping paramo assemblages. β-diversity is being increasingly used as an alternative biodiversity metric, as opposed to species richness, to guide spatial conservation planning (Kattan et al., 2004; Socolar et al., 2016). Our results on the spatial distribution of different components of the β-diversity emphasize the importance of considering β-diversity in conservation planning to preserve the species or evolutionary diversity of paramos biota.
